Reminding us of the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill to establish the organization of trade unions as a citizenship.
“Just as trade unions die, so die middle-class jobs,” said Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
Therefore, I am proud to present the Employee Empowerment Act together with the Civil Rights Icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal possibilities for discrimination on the basis of the organization of trade unions as for other forms of discrimination – and thus stops anti-trade unionist forces.
The supplementation of the national labour law to provide an opportunity for workers exposed to discrimination to organize a trade union representation to sue for justice in a civil court - and for compensation or penalties - is a meaningful and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative – at least not according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill propose is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks unions have been exposed to in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country – Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remembered when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to association in a breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to pass a constitution to ensure that the militarized autocracy would replace Hedki Tojos with democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions played a role in the creation of a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly recognized that "the rights of workers to union and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Hitler’s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing the fact that the workers would have to organize themselves and raise their voice in the new nation, the Germans introduced a clause that explicitly stated: "The right to establish associations to secure and improve labour and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or business.
Agreements that restrict or aim to degrade this right are null and null and are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global agreement, Roosevelt and the other authors added a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form or join trade unions to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labour rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to form civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to establish a trade union – and then that this union should participate in collective negotiations as an equivalent partner with companies and government agencies – must be protected.
After these rights have been under attack in America, it is indeed very wise to recall the American ideal, according to which the working population must have the right to unite and be heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
The story is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the labour movement did not restrict the strength of the nation, but rather increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions of people, work has miraculously created a market for industry and lifted the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and we should do so.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of citizens' rights as a protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representations - has long been delayed.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that America has made great in the past and repaid the promise of democracy.
