Putin calls for Kiev to start "state talks" with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin on Sunday called for the Ukrainian government to cease fighting against separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on the “state” of the abolition region.
His spokesman Dimitri Peskov later made it clear that Putin did not mean that the separatist-controlled territory of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that his status towards Ukraine would need to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
However, Putin’s call to the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal basis with the pro-Russian insurgents seems to fit the strategy he has pursued since the riots began five months ago: helping the separatists to take over territories and pressure on the Ukrainian government to enable the newly proclaimed region Novorossia to have a real independence with the West instead of Russia.
In an interview with the state television channel Channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to recapture the separatist-owned areas in the eastern Donetsk and Luhansk regions, which were captured in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have lately referred to the occupied territory as "Novorosija" or "Neurussia", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary glory period of the Russian empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who in the course of Ukrainian politicians’ campaigns for the Oct. 26 elections and while government groups attack civilian communities in separatist-held territories hope for soon peace talks "are caught up in their illusions," Itar-Tass reported.
"We must immediately begin detailed discussions, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of Southeast Ukraine in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said that Putin’s reference to statehood should be seen in the context of the larger autonomy that has been discussed by the Kiev leadership for months to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are jeopardized.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the eastern territories the necessary autonomy, Peskov said.
It is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin spokesperson’s clarification on correcting the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underlined Russia’s leadership claim in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the east as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million inhabitants are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have much greater difficulty annexed the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million inhabitants are not Russians and a large majority of pre-conflict polls gave rise to remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy addressed by Russian diplomats at international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine authority to negotiate their own trade agreements and external relations, thus giving the Kremlin de facto control of a territory that connects Russian territory with Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, annexed five months ago, is the home port for most of the Russian Navy, as well as an important commercial port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov area in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that manufacture important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko proposed in his speech on 7 June that Ukrainian legislation should consider - after new elections - additions to the Constitution, which grant the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his idea of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to that of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels whose arming and incitement Moscow is accused.
Putin’s last call to Kiev to negotiate on equal terms with the separatist leaders followed a further invasion by the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks entered eastern Ukraine over the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoasovsk, which, according to fears of Ukrainian security officials, is the first step of a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region to Crimea.
For this reason, massive civilian and military preparations have begun to establish Mariupol, a steel industry port with 500,000 inhabitants, located between Novoasovsk and the narrow access to the Crimean Peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of the EU leadership in Brussels on Saturday, urging action to prevent another Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are about to reach a point where there is no return," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not decide on concrete actions, the leadership called for the draft of further sanctions against Russia to come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukrainian crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers had to withdraw from their positions in Ilojask after two Russian tank colonies and 1,000 soldiers entered the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, Colonel Andrij Lysenko, a spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defence Council, said Saturday in Kiev.
The first 63 Ukrainian soldiers, presumably enclosed by the Russian invasion of Ilojask, were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured on Ukrainian territory a week ago, Lysenko said on Sunday.
